A BILL ENTITLED
1 AN ACT concerning
2 Criminal Procedure – Evidence – Protecting the Admissibility of Creative
3 Expression
4 (PACE Act)
5 FOR the purpose of providing that the creative expression of a criminal defendant or
6 juvenile respondent is not admissible against the defendant or respondent unless the
7 court makes certain findings, subject to a certain exception; and generally relating
8 to the admissibility of creative expression in criminal or juvenile proceedings.
9 BY adding to
10 Article – Courts and Judicial Proceedings
11 Section 10–926
12 Annotated Code of Maryland
13 (2020 Replacement Volume and 2024 Supplement)
14 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
15 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
16 Article – Courts and Judicial Proceedings
17 10–926.
18 (A) (1) IN THIS SECTION, “CREATIVE EXPRESSION” MEANS THE
19 EXPRESSION OR APPLICATION OF CREATIVITY OR IMAGINATION IN THE
20 PRODUCTION OR ARRANGEMENT OF FORMS, SOUNDS, WORDS, MOVEMENTS, OR
21 SYMBOLS.
EXPLANATION: CAPITALS INDICATE MATTER ADDED TO EXISTING LAW.
[Brackets] indicate matter deleted from exist in g l aw . *hb1346*

2 HOUSE BILL 1346
1 (2) “CREATIVE EXPRESSION” INCLUDES:
2 (I) MUSIC;
3 (II) DANCE;
4 (III) PERFORMANCE ART;
5 (IV) VISUAL ART;
6 (V) POETRY;
7 (VI) LITERATURE; AND
8 (VII) FILM.
9 (B) IN ANY CRIMINAL PROCEEDING OR JUVENILE PROCEEDING, THE
10 CREATIVE EXPRESSION OF A DEFENDANT OR RESPONDENT IS NOT ADMISSIBLE
11 AGAINST THE DEFENDANT OR RESPONDENT UNLESS THE COURT FINDS, BY CLEAR
12 AND CONVINCING EVIDENCE, THAT:
13 (1) (I) THE DEFENDANT OR RESPONDENT INTENDED THE
14 CREATIVE EXPRESSION TO BE LITERAL, RATHER THAN FIGURATIVE OR FICTIONAL;
15 OR
16 (II) IF THE CREATIVE EXPRESSION IS DERIVATIVE, THE
17 DEFENDANT INTENDED TO ADOPT THE LITERAL MEANING OF THE CREATIVE
18 EXPRESSION AS THEIR OWN;
19 (2) THE CREATIVE EXPRESSION REFERS TO THE SPECIFIC FACTS OF
20 THE ALLEGED OFFENSE;
21 (3) THE CREATIVE EXPRESSION IS RELEVANT TO A DISPUTED ISSUE
22 OF FACT; AND
23 (4) THE CREATIVE EXPRESSION HAS PROBATIVE VALUE THAT
24 CANNOT BE PROVIDED BY OTHER ADMISSIBLE EVIDENCE.
25 (C) NOTHING IN THIS SECTION PRECLUDES THE ADMISSION OF CREATIVE
26 EXPRESSION IN JUVENILE CASES FOR THE PURPOSES OF EVALUATING,
27 RECOMMENDING, OR ORDERING REFERRAL TO MENTAL HEALTH SERVICES OR
28 DIVERSION PROGRAMS.

HOUSE BILL 1346 3
1 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect
2 October 1, 2025.

